bility, and Recovery -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKatrina's Imprint highlights the power of this sentinel American event and its continuing reverberations in contemporary politics, culture, and public policy. Published on the fifth anniversary of Hurricane Katrina, the multidisciplinary volume reflects on how history, location, access to transportation, health care, and social position feed resilience, recovery, and prospects for the future of New Orleans and the Gulf region. Essays examine the intersecting vulnerabilities that gave rise to the disaster, explore the cultural and psychic legacies of the storm, reveal how the process of rebuilding and starting over replicates past vulnerabilities, and analyze Katrina's imprint alongside American's myths of self-sufficiency. A case study of new weaknesses that have emerged in our era, this book offers an argument for why we cannot wait for the next disaster before we apply the lessons that should be learned from Katrina.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDisaster reliefxSocial aspectszGulf States. 0aDisaster reliefxSocial aspectszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAiello, John1 aAnglin, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBay, Mia1 aBoyd-Franklin, Nancy1 aDickerson, Niki1 aDowd, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDowd, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFabian, Ann1 aMizelle, Richard1 aO'Neill, Karen M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRodgers, William1 aShockley, Evie1 aStein, Lyra1 aTroutt, David1 aWailoo, Keith, eedit